
## Most common exceptions related to Collection in Java

1.IndexOutOfBoundsException
-> Throws when trying to access an invalid index in a list.
	List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
	list.add("Apple");
	list.get(5); // Throws IndexOutofBoundsException

2.NoSuchElementException
-> Throws by Iterator or Enumeration when no more elements are available.
	List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
	Iterator itr = list.iterator();
	itr.next();		// Throws NoSuchElementException (empty list)
	

3. ConcurrentModificationException
-> Thrown when a collection is modified while iterating( except through the iterator's own remove method)
	List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("A","B","C");
	for(String item : list){
		list.remove(item);	// Throws ConcurrentModificationException
	}

4.IlleStateException
-> Thrown by Iterator when remove() and add() is called.
	Iterator<String> itr = list.iterator();
	itr.remove();	// Throws IllegalStateException.
	
	# Can we add/modify element in list using iterator?
	-> No, But its possible with ListIterator which specifically design for list.
		( Used set() to modify the element in list )
	
	
	ListIterator<String> listIterator = list1.listIterator();
	listIterator.add("111");			// Iterator is now positioned, Element might not print unless its rewind it.
	ListIterator<String> listIterator2 = list1.listIterator(); // reset to start
	
	for (String str : list1) {
    	System.out.println(str);
	}
	
5.UnsupportedOperationException
->Thrown when an operation is not supported by the collection(e.g.adding to an immutable collection).
	List<String> list = Arrays.asList("A","B");
	list.add("C");	// Throws UnsupportedOperationException
	
6.NullPointerException
-> Thrown when null is not allowed(e.g. In TreeMap,TreeSet or when using Objects methods).
	TreeSet<String> set = new TreeSet<>();
	set.add(null); 	// Throws NullPointerException
	
7. ClassCastException
-> Thrown when trying to add incompatible type to a collection or when comparing Incompatible types.
	List list1 = new ArrayList();
	list1.add(String");
	list1.add(123);
	List<String> list2 = list1;
	String s = list2.get(1); 		// Throws ClassCastException at runtime
	
8. IllegalArgumentException
-> Thrown when an illegal or inappropriate argument is passed(e.g. Negative initial capacity)
	List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(-5);	// Throws IllegalArgumentException
	
















